did.abstract: Ann Brewer Knox was a Washington D.C. area writer and teacher of poetry and short fiction. Her writings were widely published in journals and books. This collection contains drafts of poetry and short stories, book manuscripts, publications, personal journals, correspondence, publication, teaching and other professional materials, clippings, and floppy disks documenting her personal and professional writing career. The bulk of the material dates from 1977 to 2011.

bioghist.head: Biographical note
bioghist.p: Ann Brewer Knox (1926-2011) was a Washington D.C. area writer and teacher of poetry and short fiction. Her writings were widely published in journals and books.

Ann Brewer was born in Buffalo, N.Y. on 1926 January 31, and her father, George Brewer, was a playwright who co-authored "Dark Victory." She graduated from Vassar College in 1946 and later earned a master's degree in education from Catholic University in 1970. In 1981, she received a master's degree in fine arts from Warren Wilson College (Goddard College). Ann Brewer married M. Gordon Knox in 1947, who worked for the Foreign Service. Including six children, the Knox family lived in Washington, D.C., Moscow, London, and Karachi, Pakistan during Gordon Knox's Foreign Service deployments. Ann and Gordon divorced in 1989.

As she began to write and teach full-time, Knox built a small cabin in the southern Pennsylvania Appalachian foothills. Much of her poetry reflected the natural world of her retreat and her experiences as a daughter, wife, mother, and "recovering hostess." Knox was the author of several full length poetry collections: Stonecrop (1988), Staying in Nowhere (1996), and Breathing-In (2011). She authored a book of short stories entitled Late Summer Break (1995). Her poetry was also published in two chapbooks, "Reading the Tao at Eight" (2008) and "The Dark Edge," (2004) and in numerous literary journals and reviews, including Alaska Quarterly Review, Atlanta Review, Baltimore Review, Blueline, Comstock Review, Cumberland Poetry Review, Green Mountains Review, MacGuffin, Nimrod, Plum Review, Poerty, Poets On, Potomac Review, and WordWrights. Staying is Nowhere was a winner of the SCOP-Writer's Center Co-Publication Prize in 1996, and Stonecrop was a winner of the Washington Writers' Publishing House Prize. Knox was one of the editors of the Antietam Review and a poetry editor for the Washington Writers Publishing House. She taught poetry at workshops and at the Georgetown Day School.
Knox died of a stroke on 2011 May 10 shortly after a benefit poetry reading at Cacapon State Park in Berkeley Springs, W.V.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains drafts of poetry and short fiction stories, book manuscripts, publications, personal journals, correspondence, publication material, public relations material, writing workshops material, teaching material, clippings, and floppy disks documenting the personal and professional writing career of Ann B. Knox. The bulk of the material dates from 1977 to 2011, when Knox was active in this work. Some earlier material dates from her childhood, college years, and graduate studies, circa 1935 to 1977.

The material exhibits the stages of Knox's writing, from early drafts to published products, and her connections to other DC area poets and poetry groups. Her journals, which she regularly wrote from 1977 to 2011, contain information about her writing and daily life.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains drafts of poetry and short fiction stories, book manuscripts, publications, floppy disks, and CDs documenting the writing career of Ann B. Knox. The material dates from 1977 to 2011.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into four subseries: Drafts; Book manuscripts; Publications; and Disks and CDs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains drafts of poetry and short fiction stories. Some of the drafts include edits and revisions by Ann Knox and by the other people who read drafts of her writings. Occasionally pieces of correspondence and other material were filed by Knox with the drafts.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains typed manuscripts of poetry and short stories books, inlcuding Stonecrop, Staying in Nowhere, Breathing-In, Caught Moment, Light from Another Room, Moving On, Rituals for a Journey, Reading the Tao at Eight, Being Human Wanting Something, and Eve. Some of the folders of manuscripts also contain correspondence from reviewers and publishers. The material dates from 1986 to 2011.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains published journals, articles, chapbooks, and books, which contain poems by Ann B. Knox. Including among the publications are copies of Stonecrop, Staying in Nowhere, Breathing-In, Late Summer Break, Reading the Tao at Eight, The Dark Edge, The journals and reviews include Alaska Quarterly Review, Atlanta Review, Baltimore Review, Blueline, Comstock Review, Cumberland Poetry Review, Green Mountains Review, MacGuffin, Nimrod, Plum Review, Poerty, Poets On, Potomac Review, and WordWrights. Copies of Antietam Review include interview of poets written by Knox. The material dates from 1977 to 2011.

arrangement.p: Arranged by disk size in a single oversized box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains 5 1 floppy disks, a few CDs, and one cassette tape. The disks include digital version of manuscripts, poetry drafts, personal files, journal entries, and teaching material by Ann Knox. Most of the disks are labeled but few have dates. The material dates from circa 1987 to circa 2008.

odd.head: General
odd.p: This subseries consists of one oversize box of 5 1 floppy disks, a few cds, and one cassette tape. Most of the disks are labeled but few have dates. The disks include digital version of manuscripts, poetry drafts, personal files, journal entries, and teaching material.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains personal journals, childhood poems, correspondence, publication material, public relations material, teaching material, clippings, poetry by other authors, and papers related to writing groups and workshops. This material documents the personal and professional writing and teaching career of Ann B. Knox, excluding most of her poetry and short story writings. The bulk of the material dates from 1977 to 2011, when Knox was active in this work. Some earlier material dates from her childhood, including adolescent poems, dating from circa 1935 to 1976.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into four subseries: Journals; Biographical and publishing material; Correspondence; and Writing groups, workshops, and teaching material

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged chronologically by year. Knox wrote in multiple journals at the same time, so the journals cover overlapping dates.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains journals written by of Ann B. Knox. The journal entries relate to her writing, family, daily activities, dreams, and other topics. The material dates from 1976-2011.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains childhood poems, material related to schools and colleges she attended, photos, resumes, publication material, public relations material, clippings, grant applications, mailing lists, and poetry by other authors. This material documents the personal and professional writing and teaching career of Ann B. Knox, excluding most of her poetry and short story writings. The bulk of the material dates from 1977 to 2011, when Knox was active in this work. Some earlier material dates from her childhood, including adolescent poems, and school and college material dating from circa 1935 to 1980.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged into groups of like materials with personal material placed before professional material.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains letters, postcards, cards, e-mail, and other correspondence. Some of material is personal in nature and some of the material relates to her writings. The common names in the correspondence include Rona Chang, Joan Daw, Barbara Greensburg, David Huddle, Ann Leventhal, Heather McHugh, Warren Miller, Sidney Mitchell, Steven Tapscott, and Hilary Than, and the correspondence dates from 1977 to 2011. Some correspondence is also located in other subseries folders, especially correspondence related to drafts and publishing material.
